messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- Path: /

HTTP methods (based on the controller code only)
- allMethods (meaning “all HTTP methods are accepted”): false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation / reasoning
- The controller defines an explicit GET mapping for the root path:
  - @RequestMapping(value = "/", method = RequestMethod.GET) → GET is explicitly accepted on "/".
- There is an OPTIONS handler in this controller:
  - @RequestMapping(method = RequestMethod.OPTIONS, value = "/*")
  - This annotation maps OPTIONS to the Ant-style pattern "/*", which is NOT the same literal mapping as "/" used for the GET handler. Because the question requests determination strictly from the code (no runtime/container assumptions), I have not treated the "/*" OPTIONS mapping as proof that OPTIONS is accepted on "/". Therefore OPTIONS is reported as false for the exact path "/".
- No handler in this class maps HEAD, POST, TRACE, PUT, DELETE or PATCH to "/", so those methods are reported as false for this path.
- Note: other endpoints do exist in the same controller (for example POST /login and GET /api/secured), but they are different paths and do not change which methods are allowed on "/".
- Also note: I did not assume any application-wide context path or servlet prefix because no such configuration file was provided. If the application has a context-path or prefix configured elsewhere, that prefix should be prepended to the path "/" when generating the final OpenAPI paths.
